      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/sqa-mrl5-criteria",
      "rationale": "The CFD solver (OpenFOAM v9) is maintained under a documented software quality assurance plan including version control, regression test suite covering 47 benchmark cases, and issue tracking. SQA documentation reviewed and confirmed compliant with ASME V&V 40 Gradation 3 requirements for MRL 5."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/code-verification-mrl5-criteria",
      "rationale": "Method of manufactured solutions (MMS) applied to the incompressible Navier-Stokes solver. Observed order of accuracy (p=1.97) is consistent with the theoretical second-order scheme. Verification activity documented in VR vr-code-verification. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/discretization-error-mrl5-criteria",
      "rationale": "Three-level mesh convergence study performed (coarse 2.1M, medium 5.8M, fine 14.3M cells). Grid Convergence Index (GCI) computed via Richardson extrapolation; fine-mesh GCI for hemolysis index < 2.1%. Temporal convergence confirmed with CFL < 0.5. Gradation 4 achieved as required for MRL 5."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/test-conditions-mrl5-criteria",
      "rationale": "Experimental test conditions (flow rate 3–6 L/min, rotational speed 2400–3200 RPM, blood analog viscosity 0.0035 Pa·s) are documented with calibration certificates. Five operating points bracket the clinical envelope. Measurement uncertainties quantified and propagated into validation comparisons. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/output-comparison-mrl5-criteria",
      "rationale": "Quantitative validation metric (E_norm) computed for hemolysis index at all five operating points. Mean absolute relative error = 8.3%; maximum = 14.1%. Validation uncertainty (U_val) computed per ASME V&V 20. All predictions fall within combined experimental and numerical uncertainty bands. Gradation 4 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/qoi-relevance-mrl5-criteria",
      "rationale": "The primary QOI (normalized index of hemolysis, NIH) is the clinically accepted metric for blood damage assessment per ASTM F1841. CFD-predicted NIH is directly compared against the clinical threshold (NIH < 0.01 g/100L). The QOI is identical between the validation activity and the COU. Gradation 4 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/validation-relevance-mrl5-criteria",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments used the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry — the same geometry as the COU device. Blood analog fluid properties match within 3% of clinical blood viscosity. Operating conditions span the full clinical envelope. Geometric and physiological similarity scores both exceed the Gradation 4 threshold per the Morrison scoring rubric."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/solver-error-mrl5-criteria",
      "rationale": "Iterative convergence monitored via residual norms; all simulations converged to L2 residual < 1e-6 for continuity and momentum. Round-off error assessed as negligible (double-precision arithmetic). Solver error contribution to total numerical uncertainty estimated at < 0.5% of hemolysis index prediction. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/model-form-mrl5-criteria",
      "rationale": "The k-omega SST turbulence model is selected based on systematic comparison of five turbulence models against PIV data for the FDA pump benchmark. The Giersiepen-Wurzinger hemolysis power-law model is calibrated against in-vitro hemolysis data. Model form uncertainty is bounded via sensitivity analysis across three hemolysis model parameter sets. Gradation 4 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/model-inputs-mrl5-criteria",
      "rationale": "Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification (N=10,000 samples) performed over 12 uncertain input parameters including fluid viscosity, inlet velocity profile, rotational speed tolerance, and hemolysis model coefficients. Input probability distributions derived from experimental calibration data and manufacturer specifications. 95th-percentile hemolysis prediction remains below clinical threshold. Gradation 4 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "The test samples factor pertains to the characterization of physical test specimens (e.g., pump impeller geometry tolerances, surface roughness lot-to-lot variability). For this COU, the FDA generic pump is a standardized reference geometry with fixed nominal dimensions used solely for model validation; it is not a manufactured device subject to production variability. Accordingly, test sample characterization does not apply to the validation evidence base and is formally scoped out of this credibility assessment. The scope-out is consistent with the FDA guidance on use of reference benchmark geometries for computational model validation."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Equivalency of input parameters is relevant when validation experiments are conducted on a surrogate or scaled geometry differing from the COU device. In this assessment, the validation experiments are performed on the identical FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry used in the COU simulations, with matched fluid properties and operating conditions. Because there is no surrogate-to-COU mapping required, the equivalency factor introduces no additional epistemic gap and is scoped out. The geometric and physiological similarity is instead fully captured under the Relevance of the Validation Activities factor, which is assessed at Gradation 4."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Use error assessment addresses risks arising from analyst-to-analyst variability in model setup, boundary condition specification, and post-processing. For this COU, the simulation workflow is fully automated via a validated Python-based pipeline with locked input decks under version control, eliminating manual setup steps that are the primary source of use error. An inter-analyst reproducibility study conducted in 2024 demonstrated < 1% variation in NIH predictions across three independent analysts using the automated workflow. Given the automated and locked workflow, residual use error is judged negligible and this factor is scoped out with documented procedural controls as justification."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/cou2-vad-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-review-board",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment for COU2 (VAD hemolysis prediction at MRL 5) is accepted based on the following structured evidence review. Ten of thirteen credibility factors were fully assessed; three factors (Test samples, Equivalency of input parameters, Use error) were formally scoped out with documented technical rationale confirming they introduce no unaddressed epistemic gaps for this COU. Of the ten assessed factors: all achieved levels meet or exceed required levels at MRL 5. Specifically, Discretization error (4/4), Output comparison (4/4), Relevance of QOI (4/4), Relevance of validation activities (4/4), Model form (4/4), and Model inputs (4/4) all satisfy the most stringent gradation requirements. Software QA (3/3), Numerical code verification (3/3), Test conditions (3/3), and Numerical solver error (3/3) satisfy their respective requirements. Monte Carlo UQ (N=10,000) demonstrates that the 95th-percentile hemolysis index prediction remains 23% below the clinical threshold of NIH = 0.01 g/100L across all five operating points, providing adequate safety margin under input uncertainty. The validation evidence base is directly relevant to the COU: identical device geometry, matched fluid properties, and operating conditions spanning the full clinical envelope. The provenance chain from raw experimental data through CFD predictions to decision is complete and traceable. No weakeners were identified. The credibility body of evidence is sufficient to support regulatory submission for Class III VAD hemolysis assessment.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
